		<title>By: David</title>
		<link>http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=39#comment-963</link>
		<dc:creator>David</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sat, 27 Aug 2011 19:30:27 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=39#comment-963</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[It&#039;s unfortunate that Hutton and other shoddy scholars like him have created somewhat of a setback in the study of European witchcraft specifically and pre-Christian religious practices in general.  I remeber reading in several sources how witchcraft was never a religious practice and the notion that it was is debunk and such sources invoked Hutton.  Clearly all the evidence shows otherwise. Even the pre-Christian so-called &#039;Classical&#039; sources make reference to the religious practices of the common people and their priestesses who utilized magic. Thankfully we have scholars like Max to set things in the right.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It&#8217;s unfortunate that Hutton and other shoddy scholars like him have created somewhat of a setback in the study of European witchcraft specifically and pre-Christian religious practices in general.  I remeber reading in several sources how witchcraft was never a religious practice and the notion that it was is debunk and such sources invoked Hutton.  Clearly all the evidence shows otherwise. Even the pre-Christian so-called &#8216;Classical&#8217; sources make reference to the religious practices of the common people and their priestesses who utilized magic. Thankfully we have scholars like Max to set things in the right.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
